"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999619","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-07","<p>The requested information is not readily available and can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-11-07T10:20:38.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999619/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999619/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Social Security Benefits: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the cost to the public purse of welfare and benefits fraud committed by serious and organised criminals in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","187088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999620","Home Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>The Government included in the published Serious and Organised Crime Strategy (CM9718) a series of success measures relating to the four overarching objectives that will be used to assess the impact of the new strategy (see pages 37, 47, 51, 57, 60 and 61).</p><p>The success measures will draw on information that is published routinely within, for example, the National Crime Agency’s (NCA) National Strategic Assessment of Serious and Organised Crime, HMICFRS PEEL effectiveness assessments of police forces in England and Wales, and the annual departmental reports for the Home Office and for the NCA.</p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2018-11-08T16:24:27.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999620/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999620/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-11-01","Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Serious and Organised Crime Strategy, published on 1 November 2018, whether he plans to publish the key performance indicators for that strategy.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","187089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999621","Home Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>As stated in the Serious and Organised Crime Strategy, the Regional Organised Crime Units (ROCUs) play a vital role in UK law enforcement’s response to serious and organised crime. They are the principal link between the National Crime Agency (NCA) and police forces in England and Wales. They also provide their forces with access to specialist capabilities to tackle complex and high-harm serious and organised crime.</p><p>The Government has been working with the NCA and partners across law enforcement to deliver accurate and consistent disruptions based reporting on their collective effect against serious and organised crime. This culminated in the production of NCA minimum standards for assessing and reporting disruptions against serious and organised crime earlier this year. Using these standards we are now better able to understand performance across all parts of the system. In 2017/18, ROCU operations led to 2,052 recorded disruptions in 2017/18, while their support to partners contributed to more than 2,675 further disruptions.</p><p>Going forward, the Government included in the published Serious and Organised Crime Strategy (CM9718) a series of success measures relating to the four overarching objectives that will be used to assess the impact of the new strategy (see pages 37, 47, 51, 57, 60 and 61). The success measures will draw on information that is published routinely within, for example, the National Crime Agency’s (NCA) National Strategic Assessment of Serious and Organised Crime, HMICFRS PEEL effectiveness assessments of police forces in England and Wales, and the annual departmental reports for the Home Office and for the NCA</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2018-11-08T16:11:48.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999621/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999621/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-11-01","Regional Organised Crime Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many disruptions as a result of ROCU operations were achieved in each year from their inception to date.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","187090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999622","Treasury","false","2018-11-09","<p>HMRC continually monitors its performance for processing and making VAT repayment returns (refunds). It processes around 2 million repayment returns annually. Over 90% of all repayments are authorised within 10 working days of receipt.</p><p> </p><p>As part of its responsibilities for the care and management of the VAT system, HMRC is required to make reasonable enquiries prior to making a repayment to prevent VAT fraud, which is damaging to the UK economy. It gives high priority to checking repayment returns as it is aware of the importance of cash-flow to smaller businesses.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In circumstances where HMRC takes over 30 days to process a repayment return, a Repayment Supplement is paid. Repayment Supplement is due on less than 1% of repayments received.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-11-09T14:59:36.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999622/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999622/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-11-01","VAT: Repayments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of levels of performance in processing and paying VAT refunds.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","187134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999623","Treasury","false","2018-11-09","<p>Making Tax Digital should not have an impact on the VAT refunds process nor on paying VAT refunds.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-11-09T14:59:12.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999623/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999623/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-11-01","VAT: Repayments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the new online service for VAT refunds on the time it takes to process and pay VAT refunds.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","187135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999624","Home Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>The data required to answer the first part of the question is not recorded in a way that can be reported on accurately. As well as biometric residence permits (BRPs) issued following a grant of leave to enter or remain, the total number of cards issued by the Home Office includes replacements for lost or stolen BRPs, biometric residence cards for the dependents of EEA nationals, asylum application registration cards and BRPs reissued to correct customer reported errors.</p><p>Information regarding processing times for immigration leave applications is available through the transparency data published on GOV.UK. The latest data available is for August 2018: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/in-country-migration-data-august-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/in-country-migration-data-august-2018</a></p><p /><p /> <p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-08T15:53:59.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999624/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999624/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-11-01","Immigration: Biometric Residence Permits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many biometric residence permits have been issued in the last three months; and what the average time taken has been for issuing such permits in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","186985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999625","Home Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>Individuals with indefinite leave to remain who hold legacy immigration documents can access information on GOV.UK on how to upgrade to a biometric residence permit.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-08T16:50:24.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999625/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999625/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-11-01","Immigration: Biometric Residence Permits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 176098, how his Department plans to contact people with existing leave to remain in the UK on applying for a biometric residence permit.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","186986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999626","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-07","<p>NHS England launched a 12 week public consultation on the proposed contracting arrangements for integrated care providers (ICPs) on 3 August 2018 which concluded on 26 October. More information is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/proposed-contracting-arrangements-for-icps/" target="_blank">https://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/proposed-contracting-arrangements-for-icps/</a></p><p> </p><p>No ICP contracts have been placed in England. If, subject to the outcome of the consultation, NHS England decides to make the ICP Contract available for commissioners to use, it plans to study the impact of any ICP Contract arrangements.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-07T12:28:06.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999626/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999626/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","Integrated Care Systems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of Integrated Care Provider contracts on improving (a) quality of care and (b) value for money.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","187144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999627","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-07","<p>NHS England launched a 12 week public consultation on the proposed contracting arrangements for integrated care providers (ICPs) on 3 August 2018 which concluded on 26 October. More information is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/proposed-contracting-arrangements-for-icps/" target="_blank">https://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/proposed-contracting-arrangements-for-icps/</a></p><p> </p><p>The consultation documents provide more detail about the NHS England’s current proposals for ICPs, including:</p><p>- An overview of integrated budgets; and</p><p>- A summary of the types of organisations that might hold the proposed ICP Contract.</p><p> </p><p>The draft ICP Contract has been designed to enable a more collaborative, integrated model of care to be delivered, focusing on prevention.</p><p> </p><p>The ICP proposals would do nothing to change the level of resources available in local areas, and any decision to award a new contract or change existing contracts would be for local commissioners following full engagement with patients, the public and existing providers.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-07T12:19:19.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999627/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999627/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","Integrated Care Systems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that Integrated Care Provider contracts do not divert resources away from acute services operated by the same provider.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","187145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999628","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>The adjuvanted trivalent flu vaccine is the recommended vaccine for those aged 65 years and over because it is a more effective vaccine for this age group and should offer better protection against flu compared to those previously used in the United Kingdom programme. This is explained in the Flu Vaccination Programme Delivery Guidance 2018-19 available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/flu-vaccination-programme-delivery-guidance-2018-19/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/flu-vaccination-programme-delivery-guidance-2018-19/</a></p><p> </p><p>To ensure equitable access across the UK, deliveries of this vaccine are being phased between September and November. General practices and pharmacies were informed of the phased deliveries in April 2018 and given confirmed delivery dates in August. The supply to date has been on schedule.</p><p> </p><p>With appropriate planning, all eligible patients should be able to be offered vaccine before the flu season starts.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-06T15:13:14.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999628/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999628/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 25 October 2018 to Question 183928 on Influenza: Vaccination, and with reference to the guidance, Flu Vaccination Programme Delivery Guidance 2018-19 published by NHS England, what assessment he has made of appropriateness of delivering aTIV to healthcare providers by mid-November.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","187015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999629","Treasury","false","2018-11-12","<p>We are committed to making sure every area of the country has modern and efficient infrastructure. By the end of the parliament, public capital investment will reach levels not sustained in 40 years.</p><p> </p><p>Essex will receive £19 million for local roads maintenance in 2018/19, and DfT has provided £4 million to Essex County Council for development funding for improvements to the A120. In the last 5 years access to Superfast Broadband in Clacton has risen from 77% to 98%.</p><p>The Budget announced new programmes delivered at the local level to address barriers to productivity and increased funding for existing programmes, including an additional £420 million in 2018/19 to tackle potholes, repair damaged roads, and invest in keeping bridges open and safe. The £675 million Future High Streets Fund will support and fund local areas’ plans to make their high streets and town centres fit for the future, and the Budget also announced £150 million funding pot for a new competition for small improvements projects such as roundabouts.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-11-12T17:47:02.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999629/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999629/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-11-01","Infrastructure: Clacton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps he has taking to invest in infrastructure in the Clacton region.","false","Biography information for Giles Watling","Clacton","Giles Watling","187158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999630","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland have committed to providing coverage across England, Wales and Scotland</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-09T10:51:01.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999630/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999630/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how his Department's arrangement with Citizens Advice to provide universal credit support to claimants will operate in (a) constituencies and (b) local authority areas that do not have a Citizens Advice bureau.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","187046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999631","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-07","<p>Since 2012, Ministers and Office for Civil Society officials have met regularly with Big Society Capital to discuss the contribution of social investment to tackling key social issues.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-11-07T10:04:39.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999631/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999631/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-11-01","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Big Society Capital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many meetings his Department has held with big society capital in (a) each year since 2012 and (b) 2018.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","187034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999632","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-07","<p>My department regularly meets with voluntary, community and social enterprise (VCSE) organisations to understand their views and help inform policy. We do not hold a detailed break-down of the information requested.</p><p>Social enterprises are important members of civil society and we consulted with the sector widley when developing the Civil Society Strategy. In June 2018 the Prime Minister also hosted a roundtable on social enterprise to discuss the role of social enterprise in the UK, and how the Government can support growth in this sector.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-11-07T10:05:56.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999632/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999632/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-11-01","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Social Enterprises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many meetings his Department has held with social enterprises in (a) each year since 2012 and (b) 2018.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","187035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999633","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>The State of Emergency Commission has reviewed almost 40,000 of some 125,000 applications for job reinstatements. We are aware of the concerns raised in Amnesty International's recent report about the speed and effectiveness of the appeals process. We have called on the Turkish authorities to ensure it works quickly and effectively and will continue to follow the issue closely.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-11-08T10:48:40.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999633/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999633/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Turkey: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the (a) progress and (b) fairness of appeals against the dismissal by public sector employees in Turkey since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","186987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999634","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>We have urged and will continue to urge free, fair and inclusive local elections, due to take place in March 2019. If elected representatives are accused of a crime, it is important that the legal process against them meets the highest standards. The conduct of local elections is primarily a matter for Turkey.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-11-08T10:51:37.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999634/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999634/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Turkey: Mayors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Turkish counterpart on (a) the removal from office of directly-elected mayors in that country and (b) the recent statement by President Erdogan suggesting that successful mayoral candidates in Kurdish-majority areas may also be removed following local elections.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","186988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999635","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-09","<p>​We do not believe US-China trade relations are currently impacting on international implementation of UN sanctions on North Korea. It is the shared duty of all UN Member States to strictly enforce the UN measures, agreed unanimously under ten UN Security Council resolutions. As North Korea's largest trading partner, China's ongoing enforcement of UN sanctions is key. US and China trade relations should remain a separate issue.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-11-09T13:40:30.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999635/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999635/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","China: North Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the trade dispute between the Governments of the United States and China on the implementation by China of UN sanctions against North Korea.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","186989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999636","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-09","<p>​The Foreign Secretary speaks to Foreign Minister Wang Yi on a regular basis. He last discussed North Korea with him during the UN General Assembly on 24<sup>th</sup> September. He urged China to continue to press North Korea to take concrete actions to denuclearise, and to strictly enforce sanctions on North Korea until complete, verifiable, irreversible denuclearisation has been achieved. He has not had any interaction with my North Korean counterpart.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-11-09T13:39:00.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999636/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999636/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","China: North Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in (a) China and (b) North Korea on the talks held between the leaders of those countries in Beijing on 18 June 2018; and what information his Department holds on the outcomes of those talks.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","186990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999637","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-09","<p>​The UK, alongside like-minded partners, is actively working with the international community on the urgent and comprehensive enforcement of UN measures, including the crude oil cap, through the UN Security Council, the EU, and our wider diplomatic network. We continue to have concerns about the amount of refined petroleum imported by North Korea.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-11-09T13:41:52.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999637/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999637/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","North Korea: Oil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his counterpart in North Korea on recent imports of crude oil to that country in excess of the maximum levels permitted by UN Security Council Resolution 2375.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","186991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999638","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Civil Society Strategy is a long term vision of how government will work for and with civil society.</p><p>Social enterprises are important members of civil society and the Strategy recognised the demand from the social enterprise sector for a simpler relationship with the government. Officials are currently working to implement commitments made in the Strategy and are keeping stakeholders informed and involved as this work progresses. Details of the forum for social enterprises to coordinate relations with the government will be set out in due course.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-11-07T10:07:40.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999638/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999638/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-11-01","Social Enterprises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Civil Society Strategy, when he plans to publish information on the regular forum for social enterprises to coordinate relations with Government; and whether that forum will have an independent chair.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","187036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999639","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-07","<p>There are currently 4 full-time staff working in the Centre for Social Impact Bonds within the Office for Civil Society. In addition, the department’s finance and research staff provide support to social impact bond projects on a part-time basis.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-11-07T10:08:37.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999639/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999639/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-11-01","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Social Impact Bonds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many official in his Department are working on projects related to social impact bonds.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","187037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999640","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-12","<p>The Government is strongly committed to increasing employment opportunities for disabled people, including those with autism. Taking a life course approach, we are working across Government and with local authorities, voluntary organisations and employers in the public and private sectors to achieve this. Help and support for people with autism includes:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Access to Work, a discretionary grant scheme which offers advice and practical and financial support above the level of reasonable adjustments to disabled people who are in work or about to start work. Access to Work has also put in place a Hidden Impairment Specialist Team that gives advice and guidance to help employers support employees with conditions such as Autism, Learning Disability and/or Mental Health conditions. It also offers eligible people an assessment to find out their needs at work and help to develop a support plan.</li><li>In 2017/18, the highest ever number of people received AtW payments - 33,860, up 13% on 2016/17.</li><li>Through working with Autism Alliance, we have developed the Disability Confident Autism and Neurodiversity Toolkit, to help staff from all Government Departments understand how to support people with autism and associated neuro-diverse conditions. We also developed the Disability Passport ‘About Me’ which aims to encourage disabled claimants, including individuals with autism, to disclose their disability/ health conditions at the earliest stage to their Adviser, to improve communication and ensure reasonable adjustments are put in place. Both the toolkit and passport are hosted on Autism Alliance’s website.</li><li>Also through working with Autism Alliance, we delivered Autism and Hidden Impairment training to over 1000 nominated staff across the Jobcentre Plus network. Feedback from delegates confirms that the training helped staff to understand how to support people with autism or hidden impairments into employment.</li><li>The Civil Service has committed to support the Autism Exchange Programme, and my Department is working with Ambitious about Autism to provide work placement opportunities for young people.</li><li>Through the Disability Confident scheme, DWP is engaging with employers and helping to promote the skills, talents and abilities of people with autism and associated hidden impairment conditions. Through the scheme, DWP is providing advice and support to help employers feel more confident about employing disabled people, by signposting them to appropriate advice guidance and support.</li></ul><p><em>Improving Lives: the Future of Work, Health and Disability</em>, published last year, sets out the Government’s strategy for helping people with disabilities or health conditions, including learning difficulties and autism, enter and remain in employment. Whilst the initiatives are not all aimed exclusively at autistic people, we expect that many will benefit from these initiatives.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-12T11:51:57.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999640/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999640/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Employment: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps she is taking to close the autism employment gap.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","187154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999641","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-12","<p>Over contract duration we expect 75% of Work and Health Programme (WHP) outcomes to be from participants with a disability or long term health condition. Whilst the programme is not aimed exclusively at autistic people, we expect that many will benefit from its support; we will be releasing official statistics this year. However, the programme has been warmly welcomed by WHP Providers and their supply chain, external stakeholders and, most importantly, our customers, and is already helping people into lasting work.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-12T12:03:05.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999641/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999641/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Work and Health Programme: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Health and Work Programme for autistic people.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","187155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999642","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-08","<p>Individuals with Autistic Spectrum Conditions may request that specific referral opportunities are used for their referral to the Work and Health Programme (WHP), to allow providers to recognise their support requirements, which also record any employment outcome. WHP providers are required to record in any participants Action Plan any complex needs/ additional support requirements they have been notified of, or identify themselves as part of their support. Providers have an opportunity to track employment outcomes for this customer group.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-08T13:32:21.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999642/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999642/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Work and Health Programme: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department have taken to record the employment outcomes of the Health and Work Programme for autistic people.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","187156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999643","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-08","<p>Department for Work and Pensions officials have been considering how to robustly measure the employment rate among autistic people, including whether it might be possible to collect this information through the Labour Force Survey. Recent Labour Force Survey estimates of employment among disabled people published by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) are currently subject to health warnings, while ONS investigate an unexpected increase in the number of people reporting disabilities from July-September 2017. We are awaiting further advice from ONS, following the conclusion of their investigations. We will further consider how best to collect information on employment among autistic people in the light of that advice.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-08T13:23:07.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999643/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999643/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Employment: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps she is taking (a) to measure the employment rate among autistic people and (b) to record autism in the Labour Force Survey.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","187157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999644","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-06","The Chancellor announced at Budget that the new stake limits for sub-category B2 gaming machines will come into effect when Remote Gaming Duty is increased in October 2019. There is no delay as no date had previously been set. Government considered a range of factors in determining the implementation date of the stake reduction to B2 machines, including harm from problem gambling, impact on the high street and the economic wellbeing of those who work in betting shops. It remains completely committed to taking action to protect the most vulnerable in society from the harm that these gaming machines can cause and we have been clear we expect this to be a priority for the gambling industry. ","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-11-06T18:38:53.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999644/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999644/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-11-01","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether he has undertaken an impact assessment of his Department's decision to delay the implementation of a maximum stake on fixed odds betting terminals from April 2019 to October 2019.","false","Biography information for Mr Paul Sweeney","Glasgow North East","Mr Paul Sweeney","187130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999645","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-08","<p>As set out in the Autumn Budget, The DWP will consult on the detailed design for pensions dashboards, and on how an industry-led approach could harness innovation while protecting consumers. As part of the consultation, due to be published shortly, the DWP will explore how to maximise the participation of pension schemes.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-11-08T12:43:32.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999645/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999645/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Pensions: Consumer Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans her Department has to consult on proposals for mandatory participation in pensions dashboards by pension providers.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","187095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999646","Home Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>I can confirm that the Special Grant funding provided to the Wiltshire Police and Crime Commissioner, in relation to the Salisbury and Amesbury incidents, covers mutual aid supplied by other forces.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-11-08T15:32:34.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999646/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999646/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-11-01","Wiltshire Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 11 October 2018 to Question 176435, whether support for funding will include costs incurred as a result of requests for mutual aid following the Salisbury incident and its aftermath.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","187091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999647","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>The requested information is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-06T11:45:57.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999647/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999647/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how long people have waited on average to receive the elements of universal credit that are paid on the basis of health conditions or disabilities by condition in the most recent period for which figures are available; and what comparative assessment she has made of that waiting time with the average waiting time for standard allowance.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","187124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999648","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>​The UK will recognise a Palestinian state at a time when it best serves the objective of peace. The UK continues to support efforts towards peace. We are clear that we want to see the creation of a sovereign, independent, contiguous, and viable Palestinian state - living in peace and security, side by side with Israel. Bilateral recognition in itself cannot end the occupation; without a negotiated settlement the occupation and the problems that come with it will continue.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-08T13:51:39.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999648/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999648/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Palestinians: Recognition of States","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what preconditions his Department has set for the UK to recognise the State of Palestine.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999649","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office advises against all travel to Gaza. Entry to, and exit from, Gaza can be very difficult. Permission to access Gaza is granted by either the Israeli or Egyptian authorities. Any specific request from Members of Parliament for assistance from the Government would be considered on a case-by-case basis.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-08T13:53:26.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999649/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999649/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Gaza: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Israeli counterpart on facilitating visits to Gaza for hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999650","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>The requested information is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-06T11:49:50.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999650/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999650/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in receipt of universal credit have a (a) health condition (b) disability) and (c) a diagnosis of cancer.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","187125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999651","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>​As the Prime Minister made clear to the Israeli Prime Minister in June, the UK believes there is a need for Israel to carry out a transparent, independent inquiry into protests in Gaza. During my visit to Israel in May, I also stressed the need for an independent investigation with Israeli Deputy Foreign Minister Hotovely and Israeli Minister for Regional Cooperation Hanegbi. Our Ambassador to Israel regularly discusses the situation in Gaza with Israeli officials, urging action to improve the situation. We welcome news that Israel has opened a criminal investigation into the case of Razan al Najjar.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-06T16:51:12.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999651/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999651/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Gaza: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Israeli counterpart on the (a) progress, (b) independence and (c) transparency of investigations into (i) the use of live fire and (ii) related deaths on the Gaza border in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999652","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>​Our position on the need for an independent and transparent investigation into events in Gaza is clear. The UK continues to call on all parties to engage constructively with the UN Human Rights Council and its mechanisms.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-06T16:53:36.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999652/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999652/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he has taken to encourage all parties to engage with the UN Human Rights Council commission of inquiry on the 2018 protests in the Occupied Palestinian Territory.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999653","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>For the financial year 2028/29 the total of estimated Private Finance Initiative (PFI) unitary payments for those projects in the Hospitals and Acute Health sector is £2.52 billion (or £2,515,600,000).</p><p> </p><p>Information on the estimated revenue payments for the lifetime of each PFI contract can be found on HM Treasury’s website at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data</a></p><p> </p><p>Future estimated annual PFI unitary payments for each year of a PFI contract are subject to meeting agreed performance and quality standards, contractual variations agreed between the parties, and include an annual increment for inflation, the impact of which can vary between schemes depending on the contract provisions for when it is actually applied during the year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-06T17:47:36.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999653/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999653/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","Department of Health and Social Care: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of his Department's projected spend on PFI contracts in 2028.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","186961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999654","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>The information requested is not available. The Capability for Work questionnaire UC50 and covering letter is issued to the claimant by first class mail the day after they are referred for a Work Capability Assessment. They have a period of four weeks in which to return the completed questionnaire, and are issued a further reminder letter if they have not replied within three weeks.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-06T16:28:08.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999654/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999654/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average waiting time is for a claimant of universal credit to receive a UC50 form as part of their work capability assessment as a result of a (a) health condition and (b) disability for each of those conditions and disabilities.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","187126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999655","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>​On 14 October, I discussed the Middle East Peace Process, including reconciliation efforts, with the Egyptian Foreign Minister, Sameh Shoukry, in Cairo. The UK is supportive of Egyptian efforts to facilitate the return of the legitimate Palestinian Authority to Gaza.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-08T13:55:10.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999655/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999655/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Palestinians: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Egyptian counterpart on the proposal for the  Palestinian reconciliation process to be overseen by the Egyptian Government.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999656","Department for International Development","false","2018-11-07","<p>In July 2018 the UK committed to provide up to £38 million over five years (2018-2023) to support economic development in Gaza and the West Bank. Through this programme we will increase trade and job creation across Gaza and the West Bank by helping to enable greater movement and access for people and goods. We will also provide support to facilitate the construction of the Gaza Central Desalination Plant, which will increase access to clean piped water and help replenish the Gaza aquifer, and in turn help Gazans access clean water. In addition, this UK aid programme will help to install solar panels for hospitals, businesses and households, increasing the availability of electricity in Gaza.</p><p> </p><p>Since July 2018, we have been undertaking routine design and early-implementation stage activities, such as assessing implementing partners to ensure they meet DFID’s delivery standards, clarifying and agreeing roles and responsibilities, and setting out expected outcomes, results and timelines.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-07T16:51:54.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999656/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999656/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-11-01","Gaza: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to introduce a new economic development package in Gaza to (a) increase trade (b) support job creation and (c) enhance the supply of electricity and clean water.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999657","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>​​At this highly sensitive time in the region, there is an urgent need to restart the peace process between Israelis and Palestinians. We regularly press both parties to resume direct negotiations towards a two-state solution. I discussed the issue of the Middle East Peace Process with the Israeli Ambassador to the UK on 11 October. We continue to encourage the US Administration to bring forward detailed proposals for a viable peace agreement that addresses the legitimate concerns of both parties.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-08T13:59:05.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999657/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999657/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to encourage the resumption of substantive negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999658","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-08","<p>This information is publically available on the parliamentary website: <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/</a></p><p> </p><p>A search conducted on the website for the time period 6 November 2015 to 6 November 2018 for answered written questions about Universal Credit that contain the search terms “not collected” or “not collated centrally” returns 29 results, where the answer was either wholly or partially given as either of those terms. This is less than 1.5% of all Parliamentary Questions relating to Universal Credit answered in that time period.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-08T17:32:55.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999658/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999658/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999658/answer/previousversion/83719","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999658/answer/previousversion/83719",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, (a) how many and (b)what proportion of her Department's Answers to Written Parliamentary Questions on universal credit stated that the requested information was (a) not collected and (b) not collected centrally in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","186962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999659","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>We will spend over £50 billion in 2018/19 on benefits to support disabled people and people with health conditions.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In the budget we have announced that work allowance rates will be increased by £1000 from April 2019 and uprated in line with inflation thereafter. Raising the current work allowances will direct additional funding to working disabled people by allowing them to keep more of their earnings before the earnings taper is applied. By increasing the work allowances many disabled families on UC will be £630 better off, in a package worth £1.7bn in 2023/24.</p><p> </p><p>It has also been announced that income related legacy benefits, Income Support (IS), Income Related Employment and Support Allowance and Income Based Jobseeker’s Allowance will continue for two weeks after a claim for Universal Credit has been made. This change will particularly support vulnerable claimants who may have been on benefits for some time, have little or no savings to fall back on and currently rely on regular payments at shorter intervals.</p><p> </p><p>We have also previously announced that transitional payments for former recipients of Severe Disability Premium (SDP) and protection for those who are receiving SDP as part of their existing benefit entitlement. These claimants will now only move to UC with transitional protection. Those who have already moved to UC will be considered for a lump sum payment that will be back-dated to the start of their UC claim, and will receive ongoing monthly payments.</p><p> </p><p>These regulations provide transitional support to recipients of the SDP while removing the complexity of dealing with different rules for seven different disability additions. 500,000 vulnerable people receive the SDP alongside their benefit awards. All of these people will ultimately move to UC and benefit from this enhanced support.</p><p> </p><p>Not replicating the Severe Disability Premium in UC means the government can target additional support to a wider group. UC provides a higher level of support for the most severely disabled people than the benefit it replaces, worth up to £328.32 per month.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","187027","2018-11-06T17:52:11.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999659/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999659/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effect of measures related to universal credit announced in Budget 2018 on disabled people who are (a) in work and (b) out of work.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","187026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999660","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>We will spend over £50 billion in 2018/19 on benefits to support disabled people and people with health conditions.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In the budget we have announced that work allowance rates will be increased by £1000 from April 2019 and uprated in line with inflation thereafter. Raising the current work allowances will direct additional funding to working disabled people by allowing them to keep more of their earnings before the earnings taper is applied. By increasing the work allowances many disabled families on UC will be £630 better off, in a package worth £1.7bn in 2023/24.</p><p> </p><p>It has also been announced that income related legacy benefits, Income Support (IS), Income Related Employment and Support Allowance and Income Based Jobseeker’s Allowance will continue for two weeks after a claim for Universal Credit has been made. This change will particularly support vulnerable claimants who may have been on benefits for some time, have little or no savings to fall back on and currently rely on regular payments at shorter intervals.</p><p> </p><p>We have also previously announced that transitional payments for former recipients of Severe Disability Premium (SDP) and protection for those who are receiving SDP as part of their existing benefit entitlement. These claimants will now only move to UC with transitional protection. Those who have already moved to UC will be considered for a lump sum payment that will be back-dated to the start of their UC claim, and will receive ongoing monthly payments.</p><p> </p><p>These regulations provide transitional support to recipients of the SDP while removing the complexity of dealing with different rules for seven different disability additions. 500,000 vulnerable people receive the SDP alongside their benefit awards. All of these people will ultimately move to UC and benefit from this enhanced support.</p><p> </p><p>Not replicating the Severe Disability Premium in UC means the government can target additional support to a wider group. UC provides a higher level of support for the most severely disabled people than the benefit it replaces, worth up to £328.32 per month.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","187026","2018-11-06T17:52:11.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999660/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999660/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she had made of the levels of spending on social security for disabled people as a result of the provisions of Budget 2018.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","187027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999661","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>The legacy system serves to prop up unsustainable enterprises indefinitely and trap claimants in welfare dependency. We want to support people to be self-employed when it is the right thing for them to do to be financially self-sufficient. Key to this is continuing to support people in, or considering, self-employment to progress to a level of sustained financial self-sufficiency.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that it takes time for new businesses to grow and that even established businesses can experience difficulties. Last month’s Autumn Budget announced a 12-month exemption period from the Universal Credit Minimum Income Floor (MIF) for all new gainfully self-employed claimants, and an extension of the New Enterprise Allowance programme for a further two years beyond its current expiry date of March 2019.</p><p> </p><p>We already provide a 12-month start-up period where the MIF is not applied for newly created businesses. The new 12-month exemption period will include new claims, such as from those running a long-standing business and those moving from legacy benefits to Universal Credit, whether following a change of circumstances or moved by DWP. This also includes those existing Universal Credit claimants who become gainfully self-employed.</p><p> </p><p>These changes will provide all gainfully self-employed claimants with an equal chance, and support from specially trained work coaches, to grow their earnings, prepare and adjust for the application of the MIF. Currently, we forecast that, in 2023/24 130,000 self-employed people will have the space to grow a successful business when moving on to Universal Credit</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-06T17:47:46.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999661/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999661/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of changes to universal credit announced in Budget 2018 on self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","187028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999662","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>​We have not made an assessment of this matter. The UK has encouraged Israel to carry out a transparent inquiry into the Israel Defence Forces' conduct at the border fence, and to demonstrate how this will achieve a sufficient level of independence.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-06T16:55:00.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999662/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999662/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-01","Gaza: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the level of international involvement in Israeli investigations on the use of live fire and related deaths on the Gaza border in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","186933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999663","Department for Education","false","2018-11-06","<p>Since May 2018, levy-paying employers have been able to transfer up to 10% of their unused apprenticeship service funds to non-levy paying employer(s) to pay for the training and assessment cost of the apprenticeships agreed with the receiving employer. From May 2018, when the employers became able to make levy transfers, to July 2018 [2017-18 Academic Year] less than 1% of levy funds in employer apprenticeship service accounts were used to fund apprenticeships in this way for non-levy paying employers.</p><p> </p><p>Other than through a levy transfer from a levy paying employer, apprenticeship levy funds cannot be accessed by non-levy paying employers. More information on how transfers work can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/transferring-apprenticeship-service-funds" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/transferring-apprenticeship-service-funds</a>.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-11-06T14:55:57.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999663/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999663/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-11-01","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of apprenticeship levy funds were spent by non-levy payers in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","186952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999664","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-09","<p>On 29 June 2018, the previous Secretary of State (the Rt. hon. Jeremy Hunt MP) wrote to all the organisations who were identified to take forward the recommendations in the report by the Meningococcal Working Group to confirm what actions they will take in response. Organisations were asked to respond by the end of September.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently considering the responses and plan to publish a summary of responses in due course.</p><p> </p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-09T10:19:14.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999664/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999664/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","Meningitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent discussions he has had with relevant organisations and bodies on how they plan to (a) respond to and (b) implement the recommendations set out in the Meningococcal Working Group report.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","186984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999665","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>New claimants to Universal Credit have always been able to apply for a Universal Credit Advance in their first month if they need some financial support until the first regular payment of Universal Credit is made.</p><p> </p><p>We have previously increased the maximum amount available for advances from 50 per cent to 100 per cent of the total award, and increased the repayment period from 6 months to 12 months. Last month’s Budget extended - from October 2021 - the maximum period over which an advance can be recovered, from 12 to 16 months. From October 2019, we will also reduce the maximum rate at which deductions can be made from a Universal Credit award from 40% to 30% of the standard allowance</p><p> </p><p>Additionally in the Budget, it was announced that income related legacy benefits, Income Support, income related Employment and Support Allowance and income based Jobseeker’s Allowance will continue for two weeks after a claim for Universal Credit has been made, from July 2020. This will apply to all managed migration cases and natural migration cases where a claim to Universal Credit ends entitlement to the legacy benefit. This measure means that around 1.1 million people will see a one-off gain of approximately £200, between 2020/21 and 2023/24.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-06T16:43:33.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999665/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999665/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reason the decision was taken to stop the support provided to claimants of existing benefits and tax credits for between three and five weeks when they are migrated to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","186921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999666","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-07","<p>The National Health Service must comply with its current obligations concerning National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidance. The Getting it Right First Time (GIRFT) team engage with NICE before publication of reports.</p><p> </p><p>GIRFT clinical leads liaise with the Royal Colleges / professional societies relevant to the specialty, to review the data and findings and to develop recommendations that fulfil improvements for a range of partners, including: clinicians, trusts, commissioners, sustainability and transformation partnerships, professional bodies, and national public bodies.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-07T12:22:56.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999666/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999666/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","NHS: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what his Department's policy is on decision-making by NHS Trusts in the event that recommendations from (a) Getting it Right First Time and (b) NICE are contradictory.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","187004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999667","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>In the last three years the Department has awarded 366 contracts. Management information on this type of provision is not readily available however the appropriate form of this type of standard provision is widely used in contracts across both the public and private sector.</p><p> </p><p>In the event of any contractual breach the Department would pursue a range of remedies depending on the severity. Remedies range from formal remediation plans, through financial redress to termination of the contract.</p><p> </p><p>To date the Department does not have any instances where a breach of the referenced terms has been pursued.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-11-06T15:45:35.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999667/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999667/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Department for Work and Pensions: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 31 October 2018 to Question 184391 on Department for Work and Pensions: Contracts, how many contracts her Department has issued with any such clauses in each of the past three years; what proportion of those contracts have been breached; and what sanctions her Department has in place in the event that the clause is breached.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","186963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999668","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-09","<p>The way in which the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) assesses and prioritises evidence is set out in the methods and processes for each of its work programmes. The NICE guideline development manual outlines the different types of evidence NICE looks at and how it is reviewed in a systematic transparent way, including observational and real-world evidence. A copy of ‘Developing NICE guidelines: the manual’ is attached.</p><p> </p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-09T10:16:57.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999668/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999668/answer","developing-nice-guidelines-the-manual.pdf","developing-nice-guidelines-the-manual.pdf","Developing NICE guidelines the manual","Developing NICE guidelines the manual","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999668/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what relative priority he attaches to non-trial evidence compared to evidence from randomised clinical trials to inform NICE and NHS commissioning guidance.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","187005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999670","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-09","<p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) does not hold information on pheasants and partridges kept in raised laying cages for the breeding of game birds for sporting purposes in England and Wales. APHA does not hold this information for Bettws Hall Game Farm.</p><p> </p><p>APHA does not maintain year on year statistics for game farms. APHA only takes a register of the number of birds usually kept on a holding, which is supplied at the time of registration by the owner/keeper of the birds.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","186943","2018-11-09T14:59:20.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999670/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999670/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-01","Partridges and Pheasants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many (a) pheasants and (b) partridges were kept in raised laying cages for the breeding of game birds for sporting purposes in England and Wales in each of the last 5 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","186942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999671","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-09","<p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) does not hold information on pheasants and partridges kept in raised laying cages for the breeding of game birds for sporting purposes in England and Wales. APHA does not hold this information for Bettws Hall Game Farm.</p><p> </p><p>APHA does not maintain year on year statistics for game farms. APHA only takes a register of the number of birds usually kept on a holding, which is supplied at the time of registration by the owner/keeper of the birds.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","186942","2018-11-09T14:59:21.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999671/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999671/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-01","Partridges and Pheasants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of (i) pheasants and (ii) partridges kept in raised laying cages by the Bettws Hall Game Farm for the breeding of game birds for sporting purposes in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","186943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999672","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-06","<p>Defra held meetings with stakeholders including the Federation of British Herpetologists during the drafting of The Animal Welfare (Licensing of Activities Involving Animals) (England) Regulations 2018 (the Regulations). These discussions helped to inform us of the effect of the Regulations on all affected businesses. An impact assessment was carried out, as required with all new regulations.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","186954","2018-11-06T17:25:32.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999672/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999672/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-01","Animals: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Federation of British Herpetologists on the implications for shops and businesses selling reptiles and related species of the new animal activities licence.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","186953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999673","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-06","<p>Defra held meetings with stakeholders including the Federation of British Herpetologists during the drafting of The Animal Welfare (Licensing of Activities Involving Animals) (England) Regulations 2018 (the Regulations). These discussions helped to inform us of the effect of the Regulations on all affected businesses. An impact assessment was carried out, as required with all new regulations.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","186953","2018-11-06T17:25:32.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999673/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999673/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-01","Animals: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of the administration of the new animal activities licence on shops and businesses holding or selling reptiles and related species.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","186954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999674","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-06","<p>Under The Animal Welfare (Licensing of Activities Involving Animals) (England) Regulations 2018 (the Regulations) local authorities are able to charge a full cost recovery fee to the applicant. Guidance has been provided to local authorities about the enforcement of the Regulations and this includes a section on fee setting. The guidance includes what the fee can include and also refers to more comprehensive guidance on fees which the Local Government Association published in June 2017. Under the Regulations, any business achieving higher welfare standards will be entitled to a longer licence with fewer inspections at lower cost.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-11-06T17:21:20.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999674/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999674/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-01","Animals: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what guidelines he and his officials have given to local authorities as to the nature and reasonable costs of inspection and licence renewal for shops and businesses holding or selling reptiles and related species under the provisions of the new animal activities licence.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","186955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999675","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-07","<p>The 2008 Health and Social Care Act’s code of practice on the prevention and control of infections requires adequate provision of hand washing facilities, information on the importance of compliance with hand hygiene for visitors, regular refresher training for health professionals and support for patients to wash their hands. The Care Quality Commission monitors compliance with this code.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Improvement leads on infection prevention and control and is developing a plan that will standardise policies and guidance on hand hygiene and will be looking at a national hand hygiene data collection and reporting methodology. This project is still in development and we will be able to advise on timelines as further updates are received from NHS Improvement.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-07T12:58:07.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999675/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999675/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-01","Hospitals: Hygiene","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2017 to Question 8915 on Hospitals: Hygiene, when he plans to publish the data on hospital hand hygiene compliance.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","187024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999676","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Animal Welfare (Licensing of Activities Involving Animals) (England) Regulations 2018 (the Regulations) came into force on 1 October and modernise and streamline the licensing system for a range of licensable activities involving animals, including the sale of pets. Anyone applying for a new licence to sell pets in England will now do so under the new Regulations. Existing licences remain in force until their expiry, which is generally 31 December 2018. The Regulations have been subject to wide consultation with interested stakeholders including the pet industry and the reforms are widely welcomed. There are no plans to extend the application of existing licences beyond their current expiry date.</p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-11-06T17:24:04.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999676/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999676/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-01","Animals: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the merits of extending the transition timetable for the new animal activities licence for shops selling reptiles and related species beyond 31 December 2018.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","186956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999677","Ministry of Justice","true","2018-11-09","<p>The tables show the numbers of self-harm incidents, assault incidents on prisoners, and assault incidents on staff, per 100 prisoners, for each prison from 2013 to 2017 inclusive.</p><p> </p><p>The Government takes very seriously its responsibility to keep prisoners safe, and we are committed to reducing the incidence of self-harm across the estate. This is why we have established a prison safety programme through which we are taking forward a comprehensive set of actions to improve safety in custody. We have invested in over 3,000 additional staff in order to deliver consistent, purposeful regimes. We have also introduced the new key worker role, under which staff can give prisoners more effective challenge and support.</p><p> </p><p>Our prison staff work incredibly hard and we are under no illusions about the challenges they face. We are taking urgent action to make prisons safer, and assaults on our staff will never be tolerated. That is why we are working with the Police and Crown Prosecution Service to ensure successful prosecutions of those who assault them. It is also why the Government supported the recently passed Assaults on Emergency Workers (Offences) Act, which increases sentences for those who attack emergency workers, including prison officers.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-11-09T14:48:47.317Z","2018-11-21T15:58:04.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999677/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999677/answer","PQ 186964 - Tables.xlsx","PQ 186964 - Tables.xlsx","PQ 186964 - Tables","PQ 186964 - Tables","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999677/answer","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999677/answer/previousversion/84165","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999677/answer/previousversion/84165",,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-01","Prisons: Crimes of Violence and Self-harm","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents of (a) self harm, (b) violence against prisoners and (c) violence against prison staff per 100 prisoners there were in each prison in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","186964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999678","Department for Education","false","2018-11-06","<p>Of the 23,712 International GCSE entries in EBacc subjects, 23,635 (99.7%) of them were taken in independent schools and 77 (0.3%) were taken in independent special schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-11-06T16:16:23.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999678/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999678/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-11-01","English Baccalaureate: IGCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 1 November 2018 to Question 183354, how many of the 23,712 international GCSE entries in EBACC subjects in 2018 were taken in (a) independent schools and (b) independent special schools.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","187032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999679","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-08","<p>Rough sleeping statistics for England are published at local authority level and are not based on population size. The Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government publishes this information annually and the latest statistics for autumn 2017 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rough-sleeping-in-england-autumn-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rough-sleeping-in-england-autumn-2017</a>.</p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-11-08T14:49:24.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999679/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999679/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-11-01","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of rough sleepers in (a) towns and cities with a population above 150,000 and (b) towns and cities with a population of under 150,000 in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","186965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999680","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-08","<table><tbody><tr><td><p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-11-08T14:43:41.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999680/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999680/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-01","Automatic Number Plate Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many successful (a) fines and (b) prosecutions have been made as a result of evidence obtained from ANPR cameras in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","186966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999681","Department for Education","false","2018-11-06","<p>The new funding is for maintained nurseries, primary and secondary schools, academies and free schools, special schools, non-maintained special schools, pupil referral units, sixth-form colleges, and special post-16 institutions that have eligible state-funded pupils. Any institution that is eligible for devolved formula capital will also be eligible for the new funding. A full list of the institutions eligible for devolved formula capital in the financial year 2018-19 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/​publications/capital-allocations</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-11-06T16:42:09.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999681/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999681/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-11-01","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 5.21 of Budget 2018 Red Book whether the £400 million for School Equipment and Maintenance Uplift applies to (a) specialist schools and (b) alternative provision.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","187038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999682","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>Postcode information for Universal Credit claimants is collected as part of the process of making their Universal Credit claim. However, postcode information for advances requested in person or by telephone is not available as only advances which are paid are recorded. For these awarded advances the postcode information is available. For advances requested online, this information is recorded but<strong> </strong>is not yet available as the Department is currently quality assuring the data.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-09T09:52:00.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999682/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999682/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 26 October 2018 to Question 182759 on Universal Credit: Wolverhampton North East, what estimate he has made of the cost of recording the postcode of applicants for universal credit advance payments (a) by telephone, (b) in person and (c) online.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","186967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999683","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We have a network of Armed Forces Champions in each Jobcentre Plus district who support work coaches in understanding the range of support available to service leavers and ensure they are actively signposted to appropriate organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Our National Employer and Partnership Team also work with national employer and partner organisations to help ex-HM armed forces service leavers into employment. In addition, HM armed forces personnel are also one of the specified priority groups for the Work and Health Programme. This allows for early voluntary entry to the programme at the most appropriate time in their claim for those who would benefit from specialist employment support to find work.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","187103","2018-11-09T09:25:47.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999683/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999683/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-01","Veterans: Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many veterans that joined the armed forces aged (a) 18 or under and (b) 19 or older have registered at Jobcentres in each region in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","187100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999684","Treasury","false","2018-11-06","<p>There is no delay as this is the first time the government has announced the date for the introduction of the £2 maximum stake on Fixed Odds Betting Terminals.</p><p> </p><p>The government made clear in May that the timing of implementation does not make any difference to the public finances as Remote Gaming Duty will be increased at the same time to offset the foregone revenue.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-11-06T15:26:47.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999684/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999684/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-11-01","Gaming Machines: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the additional tax revenue that will accrue to the public purse from fixed odds betting terminals as a result of the delay in the introduction of the maximum stake from April 2019 to October 2019.","false","Biography information for Mr Paul Sweeney","Glasgow North East","Mr Paul Sweeney","187131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999685","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-09","<p>Information on medical appointments at Army Foundation College Harrogate is not held in the format requested.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-11-09T14:17:33.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999685/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999685/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-11-01","Army Foundation College: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many medical appointments by type of appointment were made by Junior Soldiers at AFC Harrogate medical facilities in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","187101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999686","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-09","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) does not hold information on the number of veterans who were diagnosed with a mental disorder after leaving Service.</p><p> </p><p>The number of serving UK Armed Forces personnel, who enlisted aged 18 or under, and had an initial assessment at MOD Specialist Mental Health Services is provided in the following table. Figures include only those patients referred to a MOD Department of Community Mental Health or admitted to a MOD in-patient provider. Some patients can be treated wholly within the primary care setting by their GP or medical officer and are not captured in MOD management information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>UK Armed Forces personnel, who enlisted aged 18 years or under, with an initial assessment at MOD Specialist Mental Health Services, by Financial Year</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Numbers</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>2,060</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2,370</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2,370</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2,660</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2,520</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2,460</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2,320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2,240</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Notes:</strong> <br> 1. Patients may not have been aged 18 or under when they were assessed at MOD Specialist Mental Health Services.</p><p>2. Some patients seen at MOD Specialist Mental Health Services may have been assessed as having no mental disorder present.</p><p>3. Numbers are rounded</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-11-09T14:23:14.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999686/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999686/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-11-01","Armed Forces: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) veterans and (b) serving armed forces personnel that enlisted aged 18 or under have sought mental health support in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","187102"
