 GMC has the general function of promoting high standards of education and co-ordinating all stages of education to ensure that medical students and newly qualified doctors are equipped with the knowledge, skills and attitudes essential for professional practice.</p><p /><p>The training curricula for postgraduate trainee doctors is set by the relevant medical Royal College, and must meet standards set by the GMC. Whilst curricula do not necessarily highlight specific conditions, they instead emphasise the skills and approaches that a doctor must develop and maintain in order to ensure accurate and timely diagnoses and treatment plans for their patients.</p><p /><p>The GMC also sets the standards expected at undergraduate level and approves medical school curricula.  In so doing, they set out the knowledge, skills and behaviours that new United Kingdom medical graduates must be able to demonstrate. This is further detailed at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gmc-uk.org/education/undergraduate/undergrad_outcomes.asp" target="_blank">http://www.gmc-uk.org/education/undergraduate/undergrad_outcomes.asp</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","186380","2018-11-05T15:50:35.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999278/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999278/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-31","Post-traumatic Stress Disorder","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what training his Department provides to NHS doctors on (a) eye movement desensitisation and (b) reprocessing treatment for cases of post traumatic stress disorder.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","186381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999279","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>The level of unemployment in the quarter March-May 2010 was 2,508,000. This contrasts with the quarter March-May 2018 where the figure was 1,411,000 which was a decrease of over 40%.</p><p> </p><p>These statistics are from the ONS Labour Force Survey and the data is collected quarterly, so the data for May alone is not held. As with all survey data, the statistics are subject to a degree of uncertainty.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-09T10:49:03.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999279/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999279/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the level of unemployment was in (a) May 2010 and (b) May 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","186299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999280","Home Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>Independent scrutiny is a vital part of assurance that our charter operations are safe, secure and humane.</p><p>We accepted or partially accepted 16 of the 19 recommendations to the Home Office and our escorting contractor in the 2017 report. We continue to work closely with the Independent Monitoring Boards to assess their ongoing recommendations. As a result of that relationship, the Home Office has introduced new measures to further support returnees on charter flight operations.</p><p>The Immigration Minister responded to the Team Leader of the Charter Flight Monitoring Team in June 2018 in respect of the 2016 and 2017 IMB reports.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-08T16:34:06.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999280/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999280/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-31","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he has made an assessment of the implications for his Department’s policies of the recommendations contained in the Independent Monitoring Board's Charter Flights Annual Report of (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","186411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999281","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>Labour market data at a local level is collected using the ONS Annual Population Survey. Statistics on youth unemployment for Suffolk are unavailable or unreliable due to small sample sizes. Youth unemployment in the East of England was 199,000 in the quarter March-May 2010, compared to 111,000 in the quarter March-May 2018. This was a decrease by over 40%.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-09T10:39:11.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999281/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999281/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Unemployment: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the level of youth unemployment was in Suffolk in (a) May 2010 and (b) May 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","186300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999282","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>The level of unemployment in Suffolk for the year July 2009-June 2010 was 24,100, while for the year July 2017-June 2018 it was 13,600. This was a decrease of over 40%. The data is collated annually so data for May alone is not held.</p><p> </p><p>The data is from the ONS: Annual Population Survey. The sample sizes for this data are very small and so there is uncertainty around the reliability and accuracy of the Suffolk county data.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-09T10:45:10.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999282/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999282/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Unemployment: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the level of unemployment was in Suffolk in (a) May 2010 and (b) May 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","186301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999283","Department for International Development","false","2018-11-05","<p>We are concerned at the intention of Bangladesh and Burma governments to begin returns to Rakhine State by mid-November. We have stated publicly that we agree with the UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) that the conditions for safe and dignified returns do not yet exist. The access required for necessary independent monitoring by UN agencies is also not in place.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any returns must be voluntary and informed. UNHCR is engaging with the Rohingya community in Bangladesh to understand their views about returning to Rakhine State. This includes information on likely conditions to which refugees would return.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-05T14:24:50.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999283/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999283/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-31","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that the Rohingya community is party to negotiations on the repatriation of that community.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","186422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999284","Treasury","false","2018-11-05","<p>A breakdown for the Exchequer impact of the changes to the Income Tax Personal Allowance (PA) and Higher Rate Threshold (HRT) announced at the Budget 2018 on 29 October 2018 is provided in Table 1.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: Exchequer Impact of Budget 2018 announcement– “Personal Allowance and Higher Rate Threshold: increase to £12,500 and £50,000 for 2019-20 and 2020-21”, and Exchequer Impacts of the Personal Allowance and Higher Rate Threshold Elements.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Budget 2018 announcement (£ million)</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td><td><p>2020-21</p></td><td><p>2021-22</p></td><td><p>2022-23</p></td><td><p>2023-24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Personal Allowance and Higher Rate Threshold: increase to £12,500 and £50,000 for 2019-20 and 2020-21</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>-2,790</p></td><td><p>-1,935</p></td><td><p>-1,445</p></td><td><p>-1,605</p></td><td><p>-1,780</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>of which</em></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(i) Personal Allowance: increase to £12,500 for 2019-20 and 2020-21*</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>-1,980</p></td><td><p>-885</p></td><td><p>-600</p></td><td><p>-650</p></td><td><p>-725</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(ii) Higher Rate Threshold: increase to £50,000 for 2019-20 and 2020-21 (given (i))**</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>-810</p></td><td><p>-1,050</p></td><td><p>-845</p></td><td><p>-955</p></td><td><p>-1,055</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>* This line assumes no change to the Basic Rate Limit (BRL).</p><p> </p><p>** This line reflects the impact of increasing the HRT to £50,000, assuming the PA has been increased to £12,500.</p><p>The Exchequer impact above includes the impact from the Upper Earnings Limit and Upper Profits Limit for National Insurance being aligned with the Income Tax Higher Rate Threshold. Further information on the Exchequer impact from the “Personal Allowance and Higher Rate Threshold: increase to £12,500 and £50,000 in 2019-20 and 2020-21” measure can be found in “Budget 2018: policy costings”.</p><p>Totals may not sum due to rounding.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","186304 ; 186305","2018-11-05T17:28:25.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999284/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999284/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-31","Income Tax: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to table 2.1 of Budget 2018, what estimate he has made of the cost of the public purse of (a) increasing the personal allowance to £12,500 and (b) increasing the higher rate threshold to £50,000, in each year of the forecast period.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","186423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999285","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>To ensure that legacy claimants move safely onto Universal Credit, we are working closely with our stakeholders to design how we identify and support those claimants who will need extra help with the managed migration process.</p><p> </p><p>Managed migration will begin in July 2019 with a period of careful and robust testing at small scale to enable us to optimise our delivery approach for all claimants.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","186317","2018-11-09T09:31:25.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999285/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999285/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what definition of vulnerability her Department plans to use for claimants that will be transfer to universal credit under managed migration.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","186316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999286","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-09","<p>To ensure that legacy claimants move safely onto Universal Credit, we are working closely with our stakeholders to design how we identify and support those claimants who will need extra help with the managed migration process.</p><p> </p><p>Managed migration will begin in July 2019 with a period of careful and robust testing at small scale to enable us to optimise our delivery approach for all claimants.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","186316","2018-11-09T09:31:25.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999286/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999286/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what procedures her Department has put in place to identify people that are classified as (a) vulnerable and (b) having complex needs in relation to the managed migration of claimants onto universal credit.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","186317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999287","Department for Education","false","2018-11-09","<p>The number of pupils, at the end of their key stage 4 study, entering each of the requested arts subjects in state-funded schools in the last eight years can be found in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>The number of pupils, at the end of their key stage 4 study, entering each of the requested arts subjects in independent schools in the last eight years can also be found in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>We have reformed GCSEs so that they are in line with expected standards in countries with high performing education systems. The level of demand in the new arts GCSEs more consistently and rigorously assesses the knowledge and skills acquired by pupils during key stage 4.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-11-09T12:24:17.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999287/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999287/answer","186431_table_pupils_arts_ks4.pdf","186431_table_pupils_arts_ks4.pdf","186431_table_pupils_arts_ks4","186431_table_pupils_arts_ks4","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999287/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-31","Art and Design: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many students in (a) state funded schools and (b) independent schools studied (i) art and design, (ii) design and technology, (iii) drama, (iv) media, film and TV studies, (v) music and (vi) performing and expressive arts subjects to GCSE level in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","186431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999288","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>Around a third of the approximately 850 people currently employed by the National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) have outward-facing advisory roles, as part of the NCSC’s remit to provide expert, trusted guidance to help protect all sectors of the economy and members of the public. This includes around 25 communications specialists, who work in partnership with other communications specialists across government and the private sector. For reasons of National Security, we are unable to provide further breakdown of staff numbers and costs.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-11-08T12:39:55.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999288/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999288/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-31","National Cyber Security Centre: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many communications specialists are employed at the National Cyber Security Centre; and what the total salary cost of those specialists is.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999289","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Government is committed to increasing the supply of social housing and has made £9 billion available through the Affordable Homes Programme to March 2022 to deliver 250,000 new affordable homes of a wide range of tenures, including social rent.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-05T15:46:39.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999289/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999289/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-31","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to Homes England's Strategic Plan, what targets have been set for Homes England in relation to affordable housing.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","186185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999290","Treasury","false","2018-11-09","<p>Budget 2016 identified expected pressures on employer contributions to public service pensions of £2 billion. The Home Office communicated with the National Police Chiefs Council on the issue shortly after Budget 2016, explaining the need to consider the matter within the wider context of the imminent scheme valuation. The scheme valuation, carried out by the Government Actuary’s Department, is ongoing. Budget 2018 confirmed additional funding for expected costs in excess of the level envisaged at Budget 2016. Government will review police spending power and further options for reform at the provisional police funding settlement in December.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-11-09T14:09:24.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999290/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999290/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-31","Public Sector: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 31 October 2018 to Question 184429 on Public Sector: Pensions, whether the effect on budges of the previously envisaged cost was communicated to police forces in advance of the Written Statement of 6 September 2018 on quadrennial valuations of the public service pension schemes.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","186391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999291","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-13","<p>The communications specialists in the National Cyber Security Centre take the expert technical advice from the organisation and turn it into clear, accessible and usable advice and guidance, setting out the simple steps that organisations and citizens can take to protect themselves.</p><p> </p><p>Between 1 September 2017 and 31 August 2018 95 blogs and 134 pieces of guidance were published. This work is carried out in partnership with government and the private sector and a dedicated NCSC engagement team to amplify reach.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-11-13T17:45:09.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999291/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999291/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-31","National Cyber Security Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Question 61 of oral evidence given on 25 June 2018 to the Joint Committee on the National Security Strategy by Mr  Ciaran Martin, what the specific campaigns are that form the duties of communications specialists in the National Cyber Security Centre.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999292","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-05","<p>The number of claims to the Child Maintenance service made by non-resident parents with regards to recalculation of maintenance as a result of a change in their income in the years 2016, 2017 and 2018 are outlined in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>The table also includes the proportion of claims that were successful in each year.</p><p> </p><p>The proportion of successful claims in each year does not directly relate to the number of claims made in that year, as claims completed in one year could include claims made in the previous year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>Number of claims with regards to recalculation of maintenance as a result of a paying parent’s change in income</p></td><td><p>Percentage of successful claims with regards to recalculation of maintenance as a result of a paying parent’s change in income</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>73500</p></td><td><p>40%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>88500</p></td><td><p>33%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018 (YTD)</p></td><td><p>82400</p></td><td><p>30%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Note</p><p>YTD: The 2018 figures are year to date figures.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-11-05T13:05:02.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999292/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999292/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for each available year, under the Child Maintenance Service, how many claims from a non-resident parent for a recalculation of maintenance as a result of a change in the income of that parent were (a) received; and (b) successful in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","186376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999293","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Communications Act 2003 already requires broadcasters to ensure that they provide access services on linear TV. These are audio description, subtitling, and sign language services. Ofcom are responsible for administering the Code on Television Access Services which sets out what proportion of programming must have access services. The Digital Economy Act 2017 made provision for regulations to ensure that there are also access services for video on demand players. Ofcom consulted on these proposals this summer and are due to submit their report to the Secretary of State shortly.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-11-05T16:43:41.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999293/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999293/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-31","Television: Disability Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if his Department will bring forward legislative proposals to require TV broadcasters to provide Audio Description Access.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","186377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999294","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-05","<p>No assessment has been made by the Department of the effect of commercial fishing regulations on the tourism fishing sector.</p><p> </p><p>Defra has funded studies on participation rates, catches, and the economic and social benefits of sea angling, which are focussed on resident rather than tourist sea anglers.</p><p> </p><p>The largest study, Sea Angling 2012, can be found at <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140305101647/http:/www.marinemanagement.org.uk/seaangling/finalreport.htm" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140305101647/http://www.marinemanagement.org.uk/seaangling/finalreport.htm</a>.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-11-05T17:21:13.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999294/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999294/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-31","Angling: Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment has his Department made of the effect of commercial fishing regulations on the tourism fishing sector.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","186424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999295","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>Asia Bibi’s acquittal will be very welcome news to her family and those who have campaigned in Pakistan and around the world for her release. We are closely monitoring the situation and developments. The UK’s position on the death penalty in all circumstances and in all countries is well-known, we call for its abolition globally.</p><p>​</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-11-05T16:46:33.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999295/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999295/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-31","Asia Bibi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the granting of asylum to Asia Bibi following her acquital of the charge of blasphemy.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","186154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999296","Cabinet Office","true","2018-11-06","<p><del class="ministerial">The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</del> <ins class="ministerial">The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply and their response will be <strong>placed</strong> in the <strong>Library</strong>.</ins></p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-11-06T16:11:45.393Z","2018-11-20T10:15:59.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999296/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999296/answer","PQ186401.pdf","PQ186401.pdf","UKSA response ","UKSA response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999296/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999296/answer/previousversion/83529","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999296/answer/previousversion/83529","PQ186401.pdf","UKSA response ","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-31","Birth Rate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information his Department holds on the (a) birth and (b) infant mortality rate in (i) England, (ii) London and (iii) the London Borough of Lewisham for each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","186401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999297","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-07","<p>NHS Digital publishes Hospital and Community Health Services (HCHS) workforce statistics for England. These include staff working in hospital trusts and clinical commissioning groups (CCGs), but not staff working in primary care or in general practitioner surgeries, local authorities or other providers.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the full time equivalent (FTE) figures of health visitors in England, London and the London Borough of Lewisham as at 30 September in the specified years and the latest available data.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>Of which: London</p></td><td><p>Of which: London Borough of Lewisham</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>8,959</p></td><td><p>1,308</p></td><td><p>68</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>8,644</p></td><td><p>1,276</p></td><td><p>66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>8,100</p></td><td><p>1,125</p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>7,849</p></td><td><p>1,074</p></td><td><p>39</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>7,802</p></td><td><p>1,056</p></td><td><p>43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>7,687</p></td><td><p>1,118</p></td><td><p>34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>8,304</p></td><td><p>1,193</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>9,162</p></td><td><p>1,411</p></td><td><p>58</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>10,236</p></td><td><p>1,639</p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>9,521</p></td><td><p>1,556</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>8,497</p></td><td><p>1,307</p></td><td><p>66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31 July 2018</p></td><td><p>7,852</p></td><td><p>1,259</p></td><td><p>58</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS HCHS monthly workforce statistics, NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p>Due to changes in the data collection and processing methodology, figures for 2007 and 2008 are not directly comparable to figures from September 2009 onwards.</p><p> </p><p>Since September 2015 NHS Digital has been collecting Independent Healthcare Provider Workforce statistics. These statistics are collected biannually and published as experimental statistics. The following table shows the FTE figures of health visitors employed by Independent Healthcare Providers in England, as at 30 September each year since 2015 and the latest data available:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>31 March 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>957</p></td><td><p>1,132</p></td><td><p>1,240</p></td><td><p>1,187</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Independent Healthcare Provider Workforce Statistics, England, March 2018, NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p>Information is not held centrally on the number of health visitors in London and the London Borough of Lewisham from independent healthcare providers.</p><p> </p><p>As health visitors are employed by a range of organisations, including National Health Service trusts, CCGs, local authorities and private providers, current data collections do not cover the complete range of these organisations. Consequently, it is not possible to provide accurate data on the total size of the health visitor workforce.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-07T12:39:32.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999297/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999297/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-31","Health Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the number of health visitors in (a) England, (b) London and (c) the London Borough of Lewisham in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","186402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999298","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-05","<p>As detailed in Office for Budget Responsibility’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook 2018 (OBR EFO) Universal Credit is now forecast to be more generous to claimants than the legacy benefit system. This is a combination of forecasting changes which are detailed on page 150 of the OBR’s EFO as well as the impacts of the Budget 2018 which can be seen in table 4.28 and on pages 150 to 153. Therefore it is not the cost of administering the system which has caused these changes.</p><p> </p><p>In our published Universal Credit Full Business Case Summary we set out that, Universal Credit will be less costly to deliver than the legacy benefit system, and that Universal Credit operational costs break even against legacy operational savings from 2019/20 and are reduced in steady state by over £0.3 billion (circa 30%) on a like for like basis.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-05T18:18:04.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999298/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999298/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to page 146 of the Office for Budget Responsibility's Economic and Fiscal Outlook 2018, published in 29 October 2018, if she will make an assessment of the contribution of (a) the cost of administering universal credit, (b) policy changes affecting the level payable under universal credit and (c) any other factors to universal credit becoming more expensive than the legacy system would have been from 2019-20 to 2022-23.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","186220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999299","Attorney General","false","2018-11-15","<p>The Attorney General’s Office has not incurred any spending on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.</p><p>The Attorney General’s Office publishes spend over £25,000 on a monthly basis as part of its transparency data routine publication which is accessible <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=attorney-generals-office&amp;publication_type=transparency-data" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-11-15T14:50:56.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999299/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999299/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-10-31","Attorney General: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999300","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>Cabinet Office publishes spend over £25,000 on a monthly basis as part of its transparency data routine publication which is accessible <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/751545/Annex_B_Expenditure_over__25000_30-09-2018.csv/preview" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-11-08T12:43:13.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999300/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999300/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-31","Cabinet Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999301","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-05","<p>The capacity of broadcasters to meet their access service obligations is for Ofcom to assess. Ofcom’s Code requires broadcasters to achieve the highest level of provision that they can afford. Broadcasters are free to over deliver on access services, and Ofcom research shows that many do. The BBC, ITV, Channel 4 and Sky voluntarily commit to providing at least 20% of their programming with audio description, which is double their statutory obligation.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-11-05T16:45:39.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999301/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999301/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-31","Television: Disability Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect on the capacity of broadcasters to meet their access service obligations of their being permitted to spend only a maximum of one per cent of their turnover on doing so.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","186378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999302","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-11-15","<p>The Department for Business Energy and Industrial Strategy spent £3.68m on EU Exit consultancy services for the period October 2017 to September 2018. Prior to October 2017 expenditure was aggregated as part of the Department’s overall consultancy spend and cannot be reported separately.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-11-15T14:52:15.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999302/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999302/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-31","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999303","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-28","<p>DCMS spend on consultancy fees for work relating to EU Exit totals £1.2m since July 2016. The suppliers of this work are PricewaterhouseCoopers and ICF Consultancy, as well as individual contractors.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-11-28T09:45:39.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999303/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999303/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-31","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999304","Department for Education","false","2018-11-09","<p>The department has not spent money on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the European Union.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-11-09T10:46:21.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999304/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999304/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-31","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999305","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-09","<p>Defra, along with other Departments, publishes spend over £25,000 on a monthly basis as part of its transparency data routine publication which is accessible here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/dataset/91072f06-093a-41a2-b8b5-6f120ceafd62/spend-over-25-000-in-the-department-for-environment-food-and-rural-affairs" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/dataset/91072f06-093a-41a2-b8b5-6f120ceafd62/spend-over-25-000-in-the-department-for-environment-food-and-rural-affairs</a></p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-11-09T15:00:22.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999305/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999305/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-31","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999306","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-11-08","<p>The department spent a total of £3,377,000 in the period to 31 March 2018 on consultancy fees, as published in the audited Departmental Annual Report and Accounts. Expenditure recorded on departmental financial systems for the current financial year totals £728,000. The final audited expenditure will be published in the relevant Annual Report and Accounts in due course.</p>","Fareham","Suella Braverman",,"2018-11-08T11:53:23.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999306/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999306/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-31","Department for Exiting the European Union: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999307","Department for International Development","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Department for International Development has not spent any money on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-11-06T15:30:43.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999307/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999307/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-31","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999308","Department for International Trade","false","2018-11-09","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) was created in July 2016 following the result of the EU referendum and was specifically established as part of the government's EU exit strategy. Given the Department's objectives it is not possible to identify which elements of these are specifically related to EU Exit.</p><p>The amount spent on consultancy, which relates to the provision of objective advice to the Department relating to strategy, structure, management or operations in pursuit of its purposes and objectives is published in DIT's annual report and accounts and can be accessed using the following link.</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/department-for-international-trade-annual-report-and-accounts-2017-to-2018</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2018-11-09T11:31:26.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999308/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999308/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-10-31","Department for International Trade: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999309","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-08","<p>The Department for Transport has spent a total of £54,282 on external consultancy work relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2018-11-08T12:32:39.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999309/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999309/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-31","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999310","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-07","<p>Since July 2016 the Department has not incurred any costs as a result of consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-11-07T12:27:54.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999310/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999310/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-31","Department for Work and Pensions: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much her Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999311","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-07","<p>The question has been interpreted as requesting information regarding the level of consultancy spend by the core Department, as recorded in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p><p>The definition employed for capturing consultancy services spend is in line with HM Treasury guidance on the preparation of Annual Report and Accounts in which consultancy services are defined as “the provision to management of objective advice relating to strategy, structure, management or operations of an organisation, in pursuit of its purposes and objectives. Such advice will be provided outside the ‘business-as-usual’ environment when in-house skills are not available and will be time-limited. Consultancy may include the identification of options with recommendations, or assistance with (but not the delivery of) the implementation of solutions.”</p><p> </p><p>Subsequently consultancy spend is recorded on the basis of this definition. As such we are only able to report against this in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts, rather than on the basis of any different interpretation or perspective, such as reporting spend on consultancy by specific programmes such as European Union Exit.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s expenditure on consultancy services, for each of the last two financial years is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Consultancy Services (£000’s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>12,402</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>4,485</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-07T12:56:59.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999311/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999311/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-31","Department of Health and Social Care: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999312","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-08","<p>This information is not held centrally and to compile it would incur disproportionate cost. The FCO's expenditure on professional services and consultancy will be published in the annual report and accounts. Contracts awarded over £10,000 are reported on Contracts Finder.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-11-08T10:29:58.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999312/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999312/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-31","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999313","Treasury","false","2018-11-12","<p>The Treasury does not hold this data in a way that would allow us to extract the information requested from existing accounting records or central searchable databases. Therefore to locate, retrieve and extract this data would exceed the disproportionate cost threshold</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-11-12T17:47:54.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999313/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999313/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-31","Treasury: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999314","Home Office","false","2019-02-06","<p>The Home Office did not have an allocation for expenditure relating to the UK leaving the EU for the 2016/17 financial year.</p><p>For the 2017/18 financial year no expenditure on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU was recorded.</p><p>Figures for 2018/19 will be available once the Home Office’s Annual Report and Accounts are audited by the National Audit Office and laid before Parliament.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-02-06T15:17:03.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999314/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999314/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-31","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999315","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>The £1 billion additional borrowing programme, which we launched in the summer, was over subscribed with local authorities submitting a total of almost 1,000 bids exceeding £2.8 billion additional borrowing. This scale of bids helped to demonstrate local authority demand for additional borrowing and appetite to increase council house building, and helped to inform the decision to abolish the Housing Revenue Account borrowing cap.</p><p>The Autumn Budget confirmed the complete abolition of the borrowing cap with immediate effect. With the issuing of a determination that revoked the previous determinations specifying local authority limits on indebtedness, local authorities can now borrow for house building in accordance with the Prudential Code without seeking permission for borrowing from the Government. As a result, the bids that local authorities submitted for additional borrowing through the £1 billion borrowing programme have fallen away.</p><p>We anticipate that local authorities may wish to reflect on their house building plans in light of the abolition of the borrowing cap, and may wish to develop new and even more ambitious plans for house building. In light of this, it would not be appropriate to publish details about the schemes that local authorities submitted to the £1 billion borrowing programme, as these schemes may now be out of date.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","186188","2018-11-05T15:54:18.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999315/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999315/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-31","Housing Revenue Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will publish a list of the bids the Government has received from local authorities under the scheme announced in Budget 2017 to increase housing revenue account borrowing headroom.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","186186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999316","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-08","<p>The Ministry of Defence publishes spend over £25,000 on a monthly basis as part of its transparency data routine publication which is accessible at the link below:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/751545/Annex_B_Expenditure_over_25000_30-09-2018</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-11-08T14:31:56.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999316/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999316/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-31","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent on consultancy fees relating to the UK leaving the EU since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","186210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999317","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-05","<p>DCMS is the lead delivery department for the festival, and will work closely with other government departments. Further funding arrangements will be detailed in due course.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-11-05T14:40:02.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999317/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/999317/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-31","Festival of Britain: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department is lead department on the Festival of Britain funding.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","186397"
